******
[1] BSE, atypical H-type, Minas Gerais
Date: Mon 6 Sep 021
Source: OIE-WAHIS (World Animal Health Information System) 2021 [edited]
https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=39061


Bovine spongiform encephalopathy, Brazil
----------------------------------------
Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Started: 11 Jun 2021
Confirmed: 3 Sep 2021
Ended on: 3 Sep 2021
Reported: 3 Sep 2021
Reason for notification: recurrence
Last occurrence: 4 Apr 2019
Causal agent: prion (atypical BSE type H)
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory
This event pertains to the whole country.

New outbreaks
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks (1)
Outbreak location 1: Campo Azul, Minas Gerais
Started: 11 Jun 2021
Ended: 3 Sep 2021
Epidemiological unit: farm
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Cattle / 746 / 1 / 0 / 1 / 0 / 0
Affected population: 10-year-old cow, from a beef cattle breeding farm, subjected to emergency stamping out.

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive

Epidemiological comments: The Brazilian Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE) Surveillance System detected a case of atypical BSE, type H. The sample was taken from a 10-year-old beef cow destined for emergency slaughter in a slaughterhouse. After detection of the presence of prion antigens at the National Agricultural Defense Laboratory of the state of Pernambuco (LFDA/PE), the samples were sent to the OIE Reference Laboratory for BSE at the Canadian Food Inspection Agency in Lethbridge, Alberta. The results of the confirmatory test were obtained on [3 Sep 2021]. This is the 4th case of atypical BSE identified during 23 years of surveillance in Brazil. The last case was detected in 2019. This case and the case reported in the State of Mato Grosso are isolated events, detected close to each other. The specified risk materials were duly removed and destroyed. The meat and other products of this animal will not enter the food chain and do not represent a risk to ruminant populations. The investigation has been completed.

Control measures applied in domestic: quarantine; traceability; screening; selective killing and disposal; official disposal of carcasses, by-products, and waste; official destruction of animals products

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA), National Centre for Animal Disease (NCAD), Lethbridge Laboratory OIE Reference Laboratory
Species / Test / Test date / Result
Cattle / Antigen detection Western blot (Ag Western blot) / 3 Sep 2021 / positive

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

