[These reports complement the information already covered in ProMED-mail posting 20210906.8650185.

The OIE recognizes Brazil as a country having negligible risk status for BSE (see https://www.oie.int/app/uploads/2021/05/a-r17-2021-bse.pdf). Cases of atypical BSE do not impact the official BSE risk status of a country, and therefore, this latest detection will not change the negligible risk status of Brazil.

The following has been extracted from "Bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) OIE Portal" at https://www.oie.int/en/disease/bovine-spongiform-encephalopathy/#ui-id-1.

Classical versus atypical BSE:

"There is a distinction to be made between these 2 forms or strains:

"Classical BSE occurs through the consumption of contaminated feed (see section 'transmission and spread'). Whilst classical BSE was identified as a significant threat in the 90s, its occurrence has markedly decreased over the past years, as a result of the successful implementation of effective control measures and is now estimated to be extremely low (close to 0 cases).

"Atypical BSE refers to naturally and sporadically occurring forms, which are believed to occur in all cattle populations at a very low rate, and which have only been identified in older cattle when conducting intensive surveillance.

"In the early 2000s, atypical prions causing atypical BSE were identified as the result of enhanced surveillance for transmissible spongiform encephalopathies. The number of cases of atypical BSE is negligible.

"Indeed, whilst to date there is no evidence that atypical BSE is transmissible, recycling of the atypical BSE agent has not been ruled out, and therefore measures to manage exposure risk in the feed chain continue to be recommended as a precautionary measure". - Mod.CRD

